#X text 41 24 [score] has a 'tempo' syntax where 'tempo 60' internally sets the bpm to 60! You can also previously set a beat length with the 'beat' message \, as in 'beat 3/8' for the beat length. The 'timesig' message is necessary to specify the time signature and allow [score] to count the number of beats in a bar \, as in 'timesig 12/8'. The default values if you don't specify anything is 'beat 1/4' \, 'timesig 4/4' and 'tempo 120'. These parameters come out the mid 'data' outlet., f 68;
#X text 41 124 The "|" symbol is the syntax for bars - like in [else/sequence] and [else/pattern]. This sets a bar number which is output at the 'data' outlet along with the messages above and whatever else that you specify in the score that is not a list starting with a timestamp., f 68;
#X text 41 176 Beat lenght \, Time signature and Tempo changes are possible and need to be specified after any bar symbol. The 'timesig' message has the same format as in the [metronome] object., f 68;
#X text 41 218 Note events are specified as lists that start with a number that represent the tempo head within the bar. So "1" means the head of the first beat \, 1.5 is an eight note after the first beat and so on. It is also possible to set the fractional part as a fraction \, as in 1.1/2 (which is the same as 1.5). Whatever follows this timestamp comes out in the 'event' left outlet and you can treat it in any way you want to. If nothing follows the number \, a bang comes out as in this example., f 68;
